{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_herring_ver01/data/sn83045499/00393342341/1938021601/0372.xml":{"full_text":"BRINGING UP FATHER\nNO-BUT YOU ARE MY\nSECRETARY-SO I HAVE\nTO I WANT YOU TO\nGET MG LANAAZE'5\n'PHONE NUMBER FOB\n\nWELL-FOB GOODNESS\nSAKE-HE MUST HAVE\nFORGOTTEN TO GET\nIS THAT YOU? FOR\nHEAVEN'S SAKE\nWHERE ARE YOU\nI TOLD YOU TO LOOK\nup aar lama:ze's\nHUMBER IN THE\n'PHONE BOOR\nBy GEORGE McMANUS\ni\nI'AA AT AAR. LAMAZE'S PLACE\nI CAME OVER HERE TO GET IT7\nBUT HE ISN'T HERE-- YOU\nCAUL- ME BACK AND IF I AN\nSWER YOU'LL KNOW THAT IT\nIS HIS NUMBER-BUT I WAS,\nJUST THINKING IF YOU DONT\nCAUL BACK-HOW\nWILL I KNOW r>\nf\nMarine News\nNORTHLAND\nBRINGS 21\nFROM SOUTH\ni\nTli motorsliip Northland. Capi. L.\nWilliams, and Purser E. P. Winch,\ndocked in Juneau late yesterday\nafternoon with 21 passengers for\nGastineau Channel.\nArrivals were: A C. Black. B.\nHertzman. G. A. La Drewa. W. J.\nPower, P. S. Key. Mrs. F. S. Key.\nC. B. McNair. W. J. Korpi. R. E.|\nRobertson, Mrs. R E. Robertson!\nOlaf Marking. Mrs. O. Marking.!\nMors O. H. Salo, Kenneth Salo. F.j\nC. Charman. Earl N. Ohmer. Mrs.\nE N. Ohmer. Mrs. J. F. Dennis.\nMrs, Eleanor Rowe, John Vognild,\nE M. Williams.\nThrough passengers for Sitka arei\nCarl Hall, S. Oaksmith. Mrs. F. V.|\nRedman, Archie Miles, Eiler Han\nsen, O. P. Wick, E. Hansen, O. S.\nLarson, Mrs. M. E. Jessup, Mrs.\nNona C. Meyer, Mrs. E. Barbeau\nand Louis Weteren.\nThe following passengers took pas\nsage for Sitka From Juneau:\nGeorge Peterson. George Boggen.\nN. A. McEachran. F. Colburn; Se\nattle via Sitka; and Ken Edwards,\nKetchikan, via Sitka.\nBERG DOCKS\nFROM SOUTH\nLAST NIGHT\nThe steamer Evelyn Berg. Capi.\nEldrcd Hanseh and Purser Eric\nBwordmaker, docked in Juneau last\nflight from the south with a cargo\nof general merchandise for Gas\ntineau Channel.\nAt Femmer's dock, the Berg un\nloaded general merchandise. At j\nthe Commercial dock, she unloaded\nseveral tons of brick and lumber,\nafter which she moved to the Alaska\nJuneau mine dock to discharge 150\ntons of poles and lumber.\nFrom here the Berg will sail\nsouth via Sitka\nLENNART ESTATE\nFIGHT WILL GO\nTO HIGHER COURT\nLitigation over ihc will c! the late\nGus Lennart of Jun\" u will be tar\nried to the higher court, it wes in\ndicated yesterday when Attorney\nPrank Foster, representin the Red\nCross, gave oral notice of appeal\nfollowing the decision of U. S. Com\nmissioner Felix Gray setting aside\nthe Lennart \"timebook\" will and\nadmitting the claims of a brother\nand sister in Sweden.\nLennart lost his life a year ago\nnear Snettisham. in his ellects\nwas found a roughly scrawled will\nlh an old time book, leaving all\nhis estate, valued at more than $10.\n000, to the Red Cross. During pro\nbate a brother and sister were lo\ncated in Sweden who put in claims\nfor a share of the estate. Yester\nday the Commissioner ruled out the\nmake-shift will and admitted the\nclaims of the heirs. The case is\nnow expected to go to the District\nCourt.\nWhen In Need of\nDIESEL OIL\u2014STOVE OIL\nYOUR COAL CHOICE\nGENERAL HAULING\nSTORAGE and CRATING\nCALL US\nJUNEAU TRANSFER\nPhone 48\u2014Night Phone 696\nNEW ALASKAN\nHOTEL\nQo. Franklin Street\nJUNEAU--none Single O\nSteamer Movements\nNORTHBOUND\nBaranof scheduled to arrive\nFriday.\nSCHEDULED SAILINGS\nNorco scheduled to sail from\nSeattle February 18 at 10 a m.\nPrincess Norah scheduled to\nsail from Vancouver at 9 pm.\nFebruary 18.\nAlaska scheduled to sail from\nSeattle at 9 a m. February 18.\nEvelyn Berg scheduled to sail\nfrom Seattle February 23.\nfreight only.\nSOUTHBOUND SAILINGS\nNorthland southbound about\nThursday noon.\nLOCAL SAILINGS\nEstcbeth leaves every Weones-\nday night at 6 p.m., for j\nS.tka and wayports.\nDait leaves every Wednesday\nat 7 a.m. for Petersburg, Pert\nAlexander, Kake and way- j\nports.\nEILER HANSEN\nON NORTHLAND\nSuperintendent of the Pioneers'\nHome, Eiler Hansen, passed through j\nJuneau yesterday evening on the j\nmotorship Northland, returning to;\nSitka after several weeks in Cali-\nfornia.\n\"Poor business outlook. Outside?'\nasked Hansen, \"Not as bad as some\npeople claim it is. There are plenty\nof sales going on in the big depart\nment stores and you still have to\nstand in line to see a good motion\npicture show.\"\nTIDES TOMORROW\n\nHigh tide 2:31 a. m\u201e 18.2 feet\nLow tide 8:38 a. m -0.6 feet\nHigh tide 2:46 p. m\u201e 16.9 feet\nLow tide 8:49 p. m., -0.8 feet\nGAME COMMISSION\nOPENS SESSIONS\nHERE THIS EVENING\nWith a quorum present, the Al\naska Game Commission opened its\nannual sessions here this morning,\nprincipal business today dealing\nwith reports of the past year's ac\ntivity.\nPresent at the meeting were\nChairman Irving McK. Reed of\nFairbanks, Andrew A. Simons of\nLakeview, Earl N. Ohmer of Peters\nburg and Executive Officer and Sec\nretary Frank Dufresne. Commis\nsioner Frank P. Williams of St. Mi\nchael and W. E. Crouch and George\nHossick of the Biological Survey of\nWashington are aboard the Bananof\nand probably will be in here Fri\nday.\n$313 RAISED, FDR BALL\nThe sum of $313 was netted at the\nPresident\u2019s Birthday Ball at Fair\nbanks.\nHOLTS IN SOUTH\nA. B Holt, former Mayor of Pet\nersburg. is now located in the Kent,\nWashington, area, handling a Plv\nj mouth and Chrysler automobile\nagency. Mrs. Holt is with him.\nA SEATTLE\niap.\nI\nLARGE\nROOMS,\nall with\nbath\nTHIS FAMOl\u2019S HOTEL l\u00bb\nclose to the theatres and\nstores, with mat nificent\nview of mountains and har\nbor. Splendid food, perfect\ncomfort, convenience and\nRates $0.50\nSpecial Rates to\nPermanent Guests.\nALASKANS LIKL THE\n<MtL\nNEW WASHINGTON\nChatham Straits Transportation Co.\n\u201cM. S. DART\u201d\nLeaves Femmer Dock every Wednes\nday at 7 a.m. for Petersburg, Kake,\nPort Alexander and way ports.\nFreight received not later than 4\np.m. Tuesday.\nFOR INFORMATION\nMAURICE C. REABER, Phone 4622\nGirdler Sees Good Times\nTom Girdler, outspoken chairman of the Republic Steel Company, is\npictured above (right) with G. P, MacDonald, president of the Lehigh\nClub, at the club's \u201cGirdler Dinner\u201d in New York City. The steel man, in\nan address appealing for cooperation between industry and the govern\nment, said \u201cAmerica is ready for the greatest development and expansion\nthat the human race has ever known.\"\nJuneau Ski Club\nDinner Dance to\nBe Event Monday\nReservations for Annual\nAffair Are Due by To\nmorrow Night\nAlready plans have neared com\npletion for the Juneau Ski Club s\noutstanding social event of the year,\nthe annual dinner dance scheduled\nfor Monday- night in the Scottish\nRite Temple where presentation ot\nawards for the ski tournament of\nthis coming Sunday will be made.\nReservations for the banquet must\nbe made by members of the club\nby tomorrow night, Orrin Kimball,\n.social, chairman, announced this\nmorning.\nMrs. Katherine Hooker is in\ncharge of preparation of the meal,\nand Clarence Rand orchestra will\nplay for dancing later in the eve\nning.\nAmong honor guests of the eve\nning will be tournament entrants\nfrom Petersburg and Sitka. \u2018A.list\ning Mr. Kimball In arranging the\nevent are Mr. and Mrs. Theodore\nDanielsen, Mrs. W. C. Overby, Miss\nMary Simpkins, Miss Louise Kem\nper. Lu Liston and Harold Mc\nKinley.\nSets Record\nIn Monoplane\nFlies Distance of 332 Miles\nin One Hour and Sev\nen Minutes\nLOS ANGELES, Cal., Fob. 16.\u2014\nFrank W. Fuller, Jr., flying a low\nwing monoplane, set a new record\ntor 332 miles from Mills Field to\nSan Francisco. He made the flight\nin the fast time of one hour and\nseven minutes.\nLode and placer location notices\nfor sale at The Empire Office.\nICE DRIFTS\nIN HARBOR\nJuneau's harbor was full of ice\ntoday for the first time this win\nter.\nAn eighteen foot tide swelled the\nfrozen sweep of the Mendenhall\nFlats ice and broke it into many\nfloes. With the ebb of the tide, much\nice floated into Juneau's harbor.\nToday the harbor experienced the\nhighest tide since the middle of\nJanuary, and the highest tide until\nthe middle of March.\nRECENTLY MARRIED\nA miscellaneous shower was re\ncently given for Cynthia Crane,\ndaughter of Irving McK. Reed, at\nthe girls\u2019 dorm at the University of\nAlaska. Her marriage to John Crane\nrecently was a surprise announce\nment to her friends.\nNURSE ON VACATION\nClara Hoover, nurse on the staff\nof St. Joseph's Hospital at Fair\nbanks passed through Juneau Mon\nday night for Seattle, thence to Cal\nifornia on a two month vacation.\nShe recently recovered from a se\nvere attack of pneumonia.\nEmpire classifieds pay.\nCALL FOR BONO REDEMPTION\nThe City of Juneau, Alaska, by\nresolution adopted at its regular\nmeeting held February 4. 1938, ex\npressed its intention to redeem six\n\"Sewer Bonds\" general obligation of\nthe City of Juneau, in the denomin\nation of $1,000.00 each, dated March\n1. 1929, numbered from seven (7) to\ntwelve 112) inclusive, bearing inter\nest at the rate of six percent per\nannum, payable semi-annually on\nMarch 1st and September 1st, ma\nnuring March 1. 1949.\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN,\nthat the said \u201cSewer Bonds\" num\nbers seven (7) to twelve (12) in\n|elusive will be redeemed at the of\nfice of the City Clerk in Juneau.\nAlaska, on March 1. 1938. and that\nall interest will cease on said bonds\nafter that date.\nDated this 16th day of February,\n1938.\nH. I. LUCAS,\n(Seal) City Clerk\niPublication dates. Feb. 16. 23, 1933.\nI\nI\nHOTEL GASTINEAU\nEvery Effort Made for the\nComfort of Guests!\nGASTINEAU CAFE\nin connection\nAIR SERVICE INFORMATION\nLUMBER\nJuneau Lumber toils, Inc.\nRADIO\nThe following summary is com\npiled from KINY Station's latest\navailable program schedule. The\nDaily Alaska Empire cannot be re\nsponsible for last minute program\nchanges:\nWednesday\u2014Closing Schedule\n4:00 to 4:15\u2014Works Progress Ad\nministration\n4:15 to 4:30\u2014Hawaiian Echoes\n4:30 to 4:45\u2014Bing Crosby and the\nMills Brothers\n4:45 to 5:00\u2014